      <h2>1. Manual Testing (Free)</h2>

      <p>Manual testing means opening ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity, Copilot and Google, typing questions your customers would ask, and recording what comes back. It sounds basic, but it gives you the most honest picture of what real users see.</p>

      <p>The advantage is complete flexibility. You control the prompts, the phrasing, the follow-up questions. You see the full response, not a summary. You notice nuances that automated tools miss, like whether the AI hedges its recommendation or presents you as one option among many.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Everyone. This is where every business should start, regardless of budget.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> It does not scale. Checking five platforms daily for 20 keywords is hours of work. You cannot track trends over time without building your own spreadsheet. And your results are not reproducible, because AI responses vary between sessions.</p>

      <h2>2. AwarenessAI</h2>

      <p>AwarenessAI is a UK-based platform built specifically for AI search monitoring. It uses a 6 Pillars framework to assess brand visibility across multiple AI platforms. The dashboard is clear and the reporting is designed for marketing teams rather than developers.</p>

      <p>What sets it apart is the ongoing monitoring approach. Rather than one-off snapshots, AwarenessAI tracks your visibility over time, so you can see whether changes to your content are actually improving your AI presence.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> UK businesses that want structured, ongoing monitoring with a framework they can act on.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Starting at &pound;100/month, it is not cheap for small businesses. The platform is still relatively new, so features are evolving. Coverage depth varies by AI platform.</p>

      <h2>3. Otterly.ai</h2>

      <p>Otterly is one of the more polished tools in this space. It tracks your brand mentions across ChatGPT, Gemini and Perplexity with a clean, intuitive interface. The keyword tracking feature lets you monitor specific queries over time and see how your visibility changes.</p>

      <p>The setup is straightforward. Add your brand, set your keywords, and Otterly runs regular checks. The reports are easy to share with stakeholders who do not want to dig into raw data.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> SaaS and tech companies that are already thinking about AI visibility and want a dedicated tracking tool.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Pricing is in dollars, which adds currency risk for UK businesses. It does not currently track Copilot or Google AI Overviews. The analysis is descriptive rather than prescriptive. It tells you what is happening but not always what to do about it.</p>

      <h2>4. Peec AI</h2>

      <p>Peec AI positions itself as a brand monitoring tool for the AI era. It tracks how AI models perceive and represent your brand, with a focus on sentiment and accuracy rather than just presence or absence.</p>

      <p>The enterprise focus means deeper customisation. You can define specific brand attributes you want to track and monitor whether AI platforms represent them correctly. This matters for regulated industries where misrepresentation is a compliance issue.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Enterprise brands and agencies managing multiple clients who need detailed brand perception data.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Custom pricing means no transparency until you speak to sales. The platform is geared towards larger organisations, so it may be over-engineered for SMEs. Documentation and case studies are limited.</p>

      <h2>5. Profound (getprofound.ai)</h2>

      <p>Profound focuses on citation tracking. It monitors when and how AI platforms cite your content, which is the metric that matters most for content-heavy businesses. If your strategy depends on being referenced as a source, Profound gives you the data to measure that.</p>

      <p>The tool also tracks competitor citations, so you can see who the AI platforms are recommending instead of you. This competitive angle is useful for identifying content gaps.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Publishers, content marketers and businesses that rely on being cited as an authority in their field.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Citation tracking is only part of the picture. A business can be mentioned without being cited, and recommended without being linked. Starting at $99/month, it is a significant investment for a single metric.</p>

      <h2>6. DataForSEO AI Overview API</h2>

      <p>DataForSEO is not a dashboard. It is a raw API that returns structured data about Google AI Overviews for any search query. You send a query, it returns the AI Overview content, sources, and links. What you do with that data is up to you.</p>

      <p>For agencies and developers who want to build their own monitoring tools or integrate AI Overview data into existing workflows, DataForSEO is the most flexible option available. The pay-per-query pricing means you only pay for what you use.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Developers and agencies building custom tracking solutions or integrating AI Overview data into existing platforms.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> It only covers Google AI Overviews, not ChatGPT, Gemini or Perplexity. You need development resources to use it. There is no interface. If you want a ready-made dashboard, look elsewhere.</p>

      <h2>7. Semrush AI Overview Tracking</h2>

      <p>Semrush has added AI Overview tracking to its existing position tracking tool. If you already use Semrush for SEO, you can now see which of your tracked keywords trigger AI Overviews and whether your site appears in them.</p>

      <p>The integration is the selling point. You do not need a separate tool or login. AI Overview data sits alongside your existing rankings, traffic and backlink data. For teams already embedded in the Semrush workflow, this is the path of least resistance.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Businesses that already pay for Semrush and want AI Overview visibility data without adding another tool.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> It only tracks Google AI Overviews. It does not monitor ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity or Copilot. The AI Overview data is an add-on to an SEO tool, not a purpose-built AI monitoring platform. Depth of analysis is limited compared to specialist tools.</p>

      <h2>8. Ahrefs AI Content Features</h2>

      <p>Ahrefs has begun adding AI-related features to its platform, including some visibility into AI-generated search results. The familiar Ahrefs interface makes it easy to adopt for existing users.</p>

      <p>Like Semrush, the advantage is integration. If Ahrefs is already your primary SEO tool, having some AI visibility data in the same platform reduces tool sprawl and simplifies reporting.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Businesses already using Ahrefs that want basic AI search visibility data without switching tools.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> AI tracking features are still limited compared to specialist platforms. Coverage is narrow, focused primarily on Google rather than the broader AI search landscape. The features feel like additions to an SEO tool rather than a dedicated AI monitoring solution.</p>

      <h2>9. Google Search Console</h2>

      <p>Google Search Console now shows data on AI Overview appearances. You can see which queries triggered AI Overviews that included your site, along with impressions and clicks. It is free, it is official Google data, and you almost certainly already have it set up.</p>

      <p>The data is limited to Google AI Overviews, but it is the most reliable source for that specific platform. No third-party tool can match the accuracy of Google's own reporting on its own features.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Everyone. If you have a website, you should have Search Console. The AI Overview data is a bonus on top of essential SEO data you need anyway.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Only covers Google AI Overviews. No data on ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity or Copilot. Reporting is retrospective, not real-time. You see what happened, not what is happening right now. No competitor data.</p>

      <h2>10. Rank4AI Audit</h2>

      <p>Rank4AI tests your business across all six major AI platforms: ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity, Copilot, Google AI Overviews and Claude. The Five Signal Model scores your visibility across authority, content structure, technical readiness, citation strength and platform presence.</p>

      <p>The free audit gives you a baseline score and identifies the biggest gaps. The ongoing service builds on that with monitoring, strategy and implementation support. Over 1,400 UK businesses have been audited using this approach.</p>

      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> UK businesses that want a comprehensive assessment across all platforms, with clear guidance on what to fix.</p>

      <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> The free audit is a one-off snapshot, not ongoing monitoring. Ongoing support is a service engagement, not a self-serve tool. If you want a dashboard you can log into daily, one of the SaaS tools above may suit you better.</p>

      <h2>How to Choose the Right Approach</h2>

      <p>For most businesses, the right answer is a combination. Start with manual testing and Google Search Console (both free). When you have a clear picture of which platforms matter most for your audience, add a specialist tool that covers those platforms.</p>

      <p>If you are a UK business looking for a structured starting point, <a href="/free-audit/">a free Rank4AI audit</a> will show you where you stand across all six platforms before you invest in ongoing monitoring.</p>
